# Windows Enumeration - Installed Applications via Registry

## Objective

The goal of this task was to:

* Connect to a Windows target system
* Enumerate installed applications
* Identify a flag hidden within application entries

---

## Initial Access

Connected to the target system using a Netcat bind shell:

nc 192.168.233.220 4444

This provided a Windows command shell for further enumeration.

---

## Enumerating Installed Applications (WMIC)

Initial attempt:

wmic product get name,version

### Observation

This command lists MSI-installed applications only.
Not all installed programs appear here, so important entries may be missed.

---

## Registry-Based Enumeration

To get a more complete list of installed applications, the Windows registry was queried:

powershell "Get-ItemProperty HKLM:\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Uninstall*"

### Explanation

The Uninstall registry key stores information about installed applications, including:

* Display name
* Version
* Publisher
* Installation details

This method provides more comprehensive results than WMIC.

---

## Searching for Relevant Entries

To quickly identify potential flag-related entries:

powershell "Get-ItemProperty HKLM:\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Uninstall* | findstr /i flag"

### Result

An entry containing "flag" was identified.

---

## Retrieving the Flag Entry

The specific registry key was queried:

powershell "Get-ItemProperty HKLM:\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Uninstall\flag"

This revealed the flag stored within the registry entry.

---

## Key Concepts

* WMIC provides limited visibility (MSI-based applications only)
* Registry enumeration is more reliable for discovering installed applications
* The Uninstall key is a common location for application metadata
* Lab environments may store flags in unconventional places such as registry entries

---

## Additional Enumeration Methods

Other useful commands:

* wmic product get name,version
* Get-WmiObject Win32_Product
* Registry queries under HKLM Uninstall path

---

## Summary

* Gained shell access via Netcat
* Attempted application enumeration using WMIC
* Switched to registry-based enumeration for complete results
* Identified and extracted the flag from a registry entry
